segments.text: And President Williams gave us the money to buy his equipment.
Oh, Williams.
Jack.
Jack Williams and Dr. Gammon, Ray Gammon, were born 30 miles apart.
Huh.
He ride on the edge of the Virginia border, didn't he?
Yep.
And Galax.
Is it Galax?
Oh, it's from Galax.
Galax.
And Dr. Gammon and we were on the railroad.
And we're not quite sure whether his town
is in one county or the other.
One county doesn't have too good a reputation.
If I were kidding Williams, which I haven't had a chance to do, I'd say his hometown is at the end of a little one-horse spur that goes south from Pulaski.
Yes, it's just a line.
We had the through line where we lived right there at River Creek with the highest point.
of the line of the railroad, the Southern Railroad, between New York, Washington, and New Orleans.
So you see it's very nice there, but they've taken most of it off.
Do you have any recollections of Dean Bolton as a man?
Dean Bolton?
Dean Bolton was positive.
That's what I would say about him.
But he was kindly.
We've had very nice relationship with him.
Mrs. Bolton was, you could see the humor in everything.
She was quite a laugher.
Rather motherly, I would say.
I would say rather motherly, speaking of Mrs. Bolton.
Mrs. Bolton?
Mrs. Bolton was that, too.
Mrs. Bolton was lovely and gave the loveliest parties imaginable.
Let me think now about Bolton.
Well, we were on two sides in a church discussion.
I remember Ray brought up a, this is your information.
It's not going on there, is it?
Well, I can take it off if you want me to.
I don't care.
Oh, is it still running?
Oh, yes, it's running.
Oh, well, I remember we were on two sides of a church situation that's not very pleasant.
And it's better to be.
on two points, politically then, enthusiastically.
And I remember when you made a parliamentary statement, which was new to the smart aleck you.
And I remember Bolton turned around real suddenly to look as much as to say, now who's opposing me?
But it wasn't ugly.
It was just his nature.
So that's all I know.
Did you have occasion to work with him very often in your capacity?
Yes.
He was dean of the college.
Yes.
And not in charge of the history department especially unless it was something related to the college properly.
I remember something.
No, Bolton, I got along very well when we had the conference.
Oh, sure.
We all got along very well.
But Bolton and you, you had been thinking about

great issues course and Bolton had two and I can't remember how you got together on that but he was the staff at the great issues course bringing people in here including uh Churchill uh Churchill's son Randolph Churchill and uh many other prominent people and uh so no Marshall was up there in Austin and uh
And they worked that out.
And it was, I believe, much more sort of academically oriented than it is now.
Now the students have taken it over, and that's all right.
But do you think perhaps students have taken over too much of everything?
I don't know.
And I don't think we will know until we see the long run effect of it.
Well, I mean, all over the country.
Not here so much.
Yes, in other places.
Well, here we are military.
Here we are.
We have become a little more student-oriented here, but not nearly so much as the rest of the country.
Out in California?
Oh, yes.
Oh, that's terrible.
But as far as that's concerned, it's all over.
The young are not very satisfied, and I cannot say that I blame them.
Well, did you notice when Vice President Ford was here, did you happen to watch the
news that night.
And they said on national television, at conservative Texas A&M University.
So we still have the label.
That is a conservative element here from the beginning.
They dressed conservatively.
Our dinner dresses were conservative.
I remember thinking that somebody who was more chic and interested in being modern, we did have some people like that.
who were atheists and very, very modern, and what we would call modern.
And I think even now, we might say they were more radically inclined.
But I noticed that her dinner dresses were conservative, just like mine.
So it was.
The whole place was conservative.
They didn't want drunks living here or teaching here.
And they didn't want loose living people here.
There was another divorce, and two divorces, but one was quite a few years earlier.
And then another divorce, and the two married.
They were not here after that year, you see?
And that was not under Walton.
I think it was under Bolton, wasn't it?
Or anyway, there was a trip down to Houston.
There was one of the men.
He's not here anymore.
I could give you the name because I have a play on his name.
Call it something slightly different, but still like his.
And he made rather verbal, improper advances to one of the secretaries.
who reported it.
And I think it was the dean's secretary, a very nice looking young woman.
And it was reported to the then Dean Bolton, the dean of the college.
Or he may have been president.
No, he was dean then.
But he was given 24 hours to get out.
And it blew up.
Well, I should not give names.
But it blew up a little organization, which was very, very, very, you know.
And one of the members later told me, she is not living now, that wasn't it good that that happened before he and I were going to give a party together.
I could tell you the names, and it's really fun.
It's a story.
It's a story.
How was the social life living on the campus?
Oh, fine.
Oh, fine.
Did you play bridge?
Did you have teams together?
Bridge, a good bit of bridge.
But we gave up bridge because, and I'll tell you what we used to have.
We used to have the cadets as babysitters for our young children.
That's wonderful.
Now that is about, we had one for years.
And he would come and do his lessons.
Our children were quiet and well-behaved, but they had funny streets to them too, for instance.
Samarie used big words and astounded everybody by his big words.
And Billy was our elder son.
Let's see up there.
Was asked by our younger son at a certain period in his life when Camp stared him in the face.
And he asked his elder brother, Camp, would you go to Camp?
And Billy, for less than so, said,
No, they make you have fun.
So you see, there are lots of fun.
And then I told you about the children roamed all over the campus, that nice little campus of that little place we went to with only 2,000 students and six or eight PhDs.
The children could roam all over the campus.
And when the 5 o'clock whistle blew, we almost knew what time it was.
Because we had that 8 o'clock whistle, the 12 o'clock whistle, the 1 o'clock whistle, and the 5 o'clock whistle.
And when the 5 o'clock siren was a-bloo, all the children came home.
It was beautiful.
So you see, there were so many sort of home-like things.
And Dr. Walton was right.
It was sort of we looked after each other.
I remember Mrs. Riley once called me up and said, Billy,
Only about five.
Yeah, he was five years old.
And he was heading for a kindergarten, a little spring up kindergarten.
We had all sorts of little things that the mothers would get excited about our children should have.
And that was not grammatical.
And so Billy was walking down the street past the Dean Friley home just a stone's throw from us.
And on his way to this little sort of impetuous kindergarten, it just sprang up itself.
And he was wading in the gutter where there was flowing water.
So Mrs. Crowley called me up and said, your son Billy is walking in the water that's flowing down the gutter.
He'll get his feet wet.
And you see how we looked after each other?
So I went down and got home and got his shoes and socks changed.
Let's see.
What else?
Any personal touches about people?
Are you trying to dig out any?
No.
You just want things as they are.
These people are gone now.
And not many people remember things about them, what type of people they were.
And I'm afraid it will be lost.
That's what we're interested in.
What kind of people were they?
You're interested in the people as opposed or different from the college itself, from the university itself.
And how it colored the university.
I see what you're trying to do.
I think I'll write that up myself and maybe get it published and make a lot of money.
Oh, and I'll tell you what we had.
We had a, oh, you must get that.

We had the people on the campus and then later those that moved south of the campus when the campus became too crowded and the college grew larger and expanded and had more faculty as a matter of course.
They moved south, which developed that way later.
The division across Texas Avenue was a later development.
But south of the campus, they called it Oakwood, and they called it West Park, and they called it College.
College Park was over here.
But let me see.
I want to get back to where I grew up.
When we had to move, oh, that was in 39.
We moved back here in 41.
Martinson built our house.
And look how straight the lines still are after all these years.
It's a wonderful, a wonderful builder.
And, uh.
But I was trying to think.
Dr. Clark.
F.B.
Clark?
Yep.
F.B.
Clark.
I knew him.
Clark Barzilla, in other words.
Uh, Barzilla Clark.
I knew him at Hopkins, where he was getting his degree in political science.
But there was no political science department here.
It was part of the history department.
So he shifted to his minor, which was political economy.
I knew him very well.
In fact, I could show you pictures of where we had been in picnics together.
I was a library assistant there at Johns Hopkins.
in a certain section that we had departments allowed.
That's very unusual.
We should follow you here.
And that's where we found each other.
And in, let's see, I want to get back to the thing.
I want to tell you that it seemed important then.
Well, anyway, Dr. Clark then, no, he didn't follow us.
Oh, you followed?
He went up to the University of Pennsylvania, I think, first and married Ruth.
And Ruth Clark and the Clarks, we were pretty good friends.
But they never lived on the campus in our time.
They had lived there some years before, but had built south there where he had bought up a whole lot of properties, he's a good economist, and was parceling it out.
And that grew very quickly.
So we had friends out there, the Adamses, the Clarks, oh, ever so many.
came in later or had moved from the campus because they wanted to be, they wanted to live in their own home instead of what our son called the campus .
And so a good many people moved out there, but that was still part of the campus in a way.
Now I'm on to what I want to tell you.
We had a social club, the A&M College Social Club, or the thing we called the Women's Social Club.
But anyway, we had regular meetings and programs and refreshments, very tiresome.
No, they weren't tiresome when we were all fixing them by ourselves.
But when the college took over, it was punch and cookies, cookies and punch, punch and cookies, cookies and punch.
But we had a very good time there together and made a big to-do over the newcomers that they came in.
We had sometimes programs.
In fact, Ruth Clark, Dr. F.B.
Clark's wife, who died quite a few years ago, bless her, she was sweet.
I always called her Gentle Ruth.
She was program chairman, and she asked me to take over her program.
And I didn't do a thing but put on something that I had put on up at Austin College, a pantomime.
Somebody reading, I did the reading.
And I have, you may have noticed, pretty clear enunciation.
That's because I'm bilingual.
And I put that on.
It was a tale poking a little bit of fun at everything.
And I read it.
I had the two ministers' wives rolled up in a sheet, holding a sheet in front.
Then I made them roll themselves up in the sheet.
And that made the proscenium, you see, the stage setting.
And I remember many other things.
We had a circus one.
Somebody, Joe Wolcott.
Do you know Joe Wolcott?
No, I don't believe so.
The name's familiar.
Well, they hadn't been here, I believe, as long as we, and did not live on the campus.
I think they moved out there right away.
He was a sister.
And she's in the hospital, so it's no use.
And he has cataract trouble.
And we knew them not too well, but when we saw each other at the ophthalmologist, we were just so happy to see each other.
I remember several, she put on a circus, I remember, once there.
Then we also had the campus study club, which was a study of,
literatures and poetries and so on.
And I think I stumped them all by putting on one.
And they always liked it.
I always got picked on to make up programs.
And I remember I did one on world literature.
Well, that took and Tolstoy and pushed in the Russians.
And that was all new.
But it wasn't new to us, because we, as you see, are readers.
And we got a lot of books in there, too.
and some upstairs, and some in the corner in the front hall, which I'm trying to give away.
And so those two organizations tied us together too, you see, the social club.
And the social club, this is important, every Christmas gave a Christmas party to the students who didn't go home, or couldn't go home, or didn't want to go home, or were unable to go home.
We gave a party for them at Christmas.
And that was quite a big party.
And I think it was Christmas Eve we got it.
We did it.
And of course, everybody went to it.
Everybody on the campus.
All the people sitting close.
Where did they hold it?
And the students, though the students were a little hold office on invitations.
That hall was always available.
Oh, I see.
Yeah.
What was always there?
Where did they hold it?
Oh, I know why.
I know why.
The same old wife without the solariums.
They didn't have the solariums on that big.
That was Mr. Cashin.
But I think Mrs. Cashin, who's still living, is not as actively involved in this whole situation as we were.
Of course, Mrs. Camel, but I doubt that you can interview her.
But they came about a year or two before we did.
But Mrs. Marsh stole her.
But that won't do.
She died some years ago saying she had had a happy life, a good, hot life.
And she was going well satisfied and grateful for what she'd had.
She was very fine.
But she was, I think, born on the campus.
Or at least her father was head of the English department fountain.
There's a plaque in the light.
meeting room of the YMCA dedicated to fountains.
And I do not know, I believe there's some fountains living in town in Nice, because so many people, when they came here, their families dragged along.
But we didn't.
They were in Virginia.
But so many came here, including the Cashin family, the Walton family, the Maristella family.
And I don't know the other Walton family.
And so they settled around here.
But I believe the Fountain family are too far out, probably grandniece and so on.
But Mrs. Marskeller could have told you way, way back then when they used to have to drive to Bryan.
I've heard her.
Drive to Bryan in their buggies.
People didn't have cars so much in those days.
And the road was kind of.
Of course, the roads were muddy here when we first came out here.
This was developed.
There have been the college people and the Brown people have developed so many subdivisions around here and made millions.
You see, college is quite a place to make your millions anyway.
And for a while, there was antagonism between college and Brown.
But I think that sort of petered out, except maybe some of the old timers.
But we lived on the campus, and we moved to Bryant, you see.
So we didn't have that at all.
I mean, we were too busy having other things and doing other things.
We didn't have time for stuff like that.
But I think that's all right now.
But you see, I don't know if you're a historian enough to know the antagonism that has always existed from medieval times.
Isn't that so?
Town and gown.
Town and gown, always.
Town and gown.
Right.
Well, that's way back from medieval times.
Yes, ma'am.
And I think it was that, uh,
at Washington and Lee to, but not at Johns Hopkins.
Johns Hopkins wasn't that one of the first that gave PhDs in history.
It's one of the oldest.
I don't remember what I believe it was.
They advanced.
It was one of the most advanced higher education, that is, beyond the four-year collegiate.

And so, of course, I think, but I think Doug Gammon followed his head of department at Washington and Lee, who went to Johns Hopkins and knew all sorts of important people, including Woodrow Wilson, my friend.
You remember?
Oh, we had so many funny things.
Oh, well, I didn't.
We don't think about them.
Now we've gotten to thinking about them.
What else?
Anything else you want?
I can't remember any crimes.
No, not interested in that particularly.
There wasn't anything like that.
It was so peaceful.
Well, that's probably part of it.
That campus, it was secure.
What do you remember about the early days of the Depression, the effect upon the students, the effect upon the school?
The early days?
Say 1929 on, with the start of the Depression.
Our appropriations from the legislature were not badly reduced.
Cut down a little bit in the interest of the economy,
But we didn't suffer.
Being state supported, we suffered about as little as any of them.
We were reduced how much?
One quarter.
But we had two years warning.
So as I told Helen Summitt, I said, we're cutting ourselves right now.
Then we'll be prepared for that.
In other words, we didn't suffer at all.
We still went to Virginia.
We began laying aside in time.
We used to go to Virginia.
You'd see practically every summer, get up in that lovely summer.
But later that legislature over there in Austin, am I pointing in the right direction?
Anyway, I point.
You see, that's disrespectful.
They didn't understand why professors should teach only four to five hours a day.
They should have a full load, like a construction worker.
Not coming to your land.
I mean, part of architecture.
No, I'm a historian.
I'm not an architect.
Oh, you're not an architect?
I thought you were in the architect department.
No, no, I'm a historian.
Oh, you're a teacher in the history department?
I'm an archivist.
Your husband could tell you the differences.
I'm a keeper of manuscripts and papers.
archivist rather than architect.
Well, we like the word archivist very well.
That fits our way of thinking.
In fact, when we had to have a heritage club, an organization, a committee in the church to preserve all the artifacts and all that, we had quite a little time on what to call it.
And of course, our inclination was bookish.
And we thought, our kind.
But the rest of them were more emotionally interested in it.
So it got called Heritage Club, Heritage Committee.
And we're on it.
And in fact, we gave them, we're older now, and we can't do as much.
So we feel that we should give more.
And so we had given there.
And we've also gone.
We went to the meeting, I believe it was last Sunday.
before yesterday, a week ago.
And we gave them some bookcases.
Oh, that doesn't need to go on that.
It doesn't need to go on that.
Scratch it.
I will.
Take it.
When I thought, oh, well, we'll give those two old bookcases, a six-section, glassed in to put their books and other, oh, so many papers, so many pictures.
You ought to see what they have over there.
Is this the first church?
Right here?
First Presbyterian Church in Bryan, asked to see it.
And though we haven't got everything out that we need to have.
And those six bookcases were given to Dr. Gavin in two Christmases by his father in 1906 or so, when they had just been patented in 1905.
Because he was bookish, and his father encouraged it.
And the reason he went to Austin College to try out teaching in the prep department, through the influence of two
of the Mann family friends, because he loved books and had so many and received so many, just like our family did.
Our family would sit around reading in utter silence for an evening.
And then we'd notice that there was something different.
And then it would be my wonderful father, who was always smiling.
He was sitting around smiling, Edison smiling, because we were all reading instead of quarreling.
No, I don't mean that, because we didn't quarrel.
And let's see now.
So archivist, let me think.
Those two organizations, don't forget them.
The social club, which really I think was organized to do for the boys that remained here at Christmas.
And later, more people had cars and ways of transportation and so forth.
So we didn't have so many boys at that time.
But they always had the habit of inviting boys.
But the boys were rather slow about wanting to get under the eye of the professors.
They must have been a tough lot.
And then that study club, which drew us still more together, you see.
So when I was asked to join the woman's club in Bryan, which is quite it, that's an old club.
I reneged because I felt that I owed it out there to college.
We lived at college.
Now I kind of wish I had joined them because I have many friends in there.
In Bryan, you see, we have friends because we have never had these antagonisms.
We've gone to the church in Bryan.
So we have so many friends both ways.
Well, let's see.
Any more people you want?
Well, I was trying to think.
You must be Drew Pearson or something.
No.
No.
Just a curious person by nature.
No.
Well, I think not Drew Pearson, but somebody else who was trying to catch leaks, let's say.
That's the proper way to put it now.
You see, we're living right now, even though we're 85.
They tried to work.
Our son tried to get him to join.
One of them tried to get him.
It was not Drew Pearson.
I think Drew Pearson had died then.
But it was somebody else on that same line, only not as grubby as Drew Pearson tried to get him to join him for luncheon.
But fortunately, Samory had another engagement.
And as he called us up and said the other day, by the way, he's pretty high.
They don't have anybody in the State Department.
All they have is a whole lot of military people that they write up this and that about.
But has been vice consul, consul, consul general in Ethiopia, and consular for political affairs in our embassy in Rome, and is now on the same floor as Kissinger.
I don't know how much I like that.
Oh, you better delete that or they'll bug my phone.
And he doesn't tell us anything.
I was wondering, does he come home very, does he come to College Station?
Well, it's been a great while.
He came out here, and Dr. Tom Harrington.
Dr. Tom Harrington.
He is the chancellor emeritus that lived in on Creek, the Creek Road.
Carter Creek?
Back, no, not Carter, isn't that 32nd?
It's, when you go on Wayside Drive,
If you know, that leads off from Villa Maria Road.
If you turn at Wayside Drive, you will cross the street that he lives on, but it's some kind of creek.
And since he's retired, he moved to Bride.
And I think he was wise.
Because coming as Chancellor Emeritus and staying out there and being nobody, it's better to come in to Bride.
And so I think he was wise on that.
But he was so interested in Samurai, and so was this older crowd who all have died.
And I think perhaps it was instrumental in some of this Rotary.

He was also, he could have had a Fulbright, but he preferred a Rotary because it was paid off in American money, and the Fulbright scholarship or fellowship or whatever was paid up in the European money.
American money, pretty smart.
And he gets, he was down here, I can't remember what year, that's when he was in Ethiopia.
And Dr. Tom Harrington, who was in charge, he had retired as chancellor, but he was doing something about international students or something like that.
And he asked Ray, Sam Ray, to talk, to give a talk at the
the Memorial Center in one of the rooms up there.
I think it was the main ballroom.
And about his work.
But he calls up very frequently.
But he has a pretty important job.
Every bit of mail, every bit of pouch, the couriers carry their pouches strapped to their wrists with very secret documents
And they don't leak, I think.
And so all of that that comes in, he has to analyze and send it in the right direction.
So he called up one particular time.
And he always calls up on special occasions.
But I suppose we talk to each other about two or three times a month.
He called up, and there was no particular reason for it.
And I said, well, what do you know?
And he says, everything.
But I'm not allowed to tell it.
So that, but nothing ever gets into the battalion or into the, who at McQuillan used to be in charge of the students, the ex-students, or the alumni, or whatever.
Former students.
And alumni.
The Association of the Former Students.
The Former Students Association, but they call it.
They don't know the word alumni, I guess.
But it never gets in any of their records.
And he's risen.
He's in the secretariat, same floor as Kissinger and those other people.
And I could tell quite a few things.
that I have sort of survived because I like to think about these things in time together and make a life, a story, a world of them.
So I think you've about drained me now.
I think I've drained you both.
I certainly appreciate it.
I'm going to cut this off.
But I would like to turn it up.
He and Cam were here on the campus before we came and before either of them married.
and Camel from Illinois, I think, and Coper from Kentucky.
And D.B.
Coper, he's not the one that's sick, is he?
That's what I'd heard.
Well, Mrs. Coper was raised in Bryan, and she would know a lot about it here, more than we, I'd say.
And I don't know if you're telling her that I suggested her because she knew about as much as Mrs. Marsteller.
who was raised on the campus and has died.
That's important.
Sarah Allen Cooper, do you know Allen Academy?
She was the daughter of the Allens.
One of the older ones.
They're gone.
And Mrs. Darnell, she's not living around here, she's a sister.
But Mrs. Cooper, unless they would be, she would be disturbed.
She's very tense and nervous.
I don't know how good she would...
I mean, you have to be lively, but not tense.
And so I don't know whether you could, but she was raised in Brian.
Therefore, she didn't know.
And she and Margaret Camel, Margaret Camel was in Palestine and came visiting Sarah Allen for events here.
They were both from Randall-Macon.
They'd gone to college at Randall-Macon in Virginia, Pittsburgh.
And so she would visit.
So Dr. Camel, head of the Modern Language, and Phoebe Coker, in the English department, he never became head of it, but he became archivist.
Yes, he was.
He was the first one.
And they courted the two girls.
You see, they were blind dating and so on.
So they, and that,
Mrs. Hamill is not the one to see into the side.
She's pretty far along in arthritis and things like that.
But otherwise, I would tell her she's a very smart girl, woman, and has a good education over there around making girls color.
But Mrs. Coker is quick and snappy like that, and I don't know how she would take questions like that.
So, I don't mean there's anything wrong with their mind.
No, no.
